<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>viscidiflorus</i> is dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>arbuscula</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i> and <i>Purshia</i> <i>tridentata</i>. Herbs are typically present including <i>Achnatherum</i> <i>occidentale</i>, <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Elymus</i> <i>elymoides</i>, <i>Festuca</i> <i>idahoensis</i>, <i>Lupinus</i> <i>argenteus</i> and <i>Poa</i> <i>secunda</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>occidentalis</i> and <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse or grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus</i> > 50% relative cover and generally > 5% absolute cover (DiPaolo et al. 2015a, Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub layer and without significant cover of <i>Artemisia tridentata </i>or <i>Purshia tridentata</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li>The shrub layer is dominated by <i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus</i> with 3 - 35% cover (NatureServe 2019).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Flat to moderately sloping, disturbed sites on slopes, ridges and in valleys. Soils vary from silt loam, sandy loam, loamy sand, and silty clay loam.  </div>
</div>

        
