<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus</i> is a fast-growing, early seral shrub that establishes following disturbance. It blooms summer to fall and fruits in fall and winter. The wind-dispersed seeds germinate in the spring. The ecology varies by subspecies (Tirmenstein 1999i). Five subspecies occur in the western U.S. <br/>
<br/>
Stands of this alliance exist in the colder desert regions of California. They typically grow in disturbed areas, whether naturally disturbed by intermittent flooding or disturbed by fire, overgrazing, clearings, or mine tailings. Plants colonize and persist for at least 10 years, including after changes in grazing regimes or after fires. They are often transitional to sagebrush (<i>Artemisia </i>spp.) shrublands and pinyon-juniper woodlands (Tirmenstein 1999i, Young and Evans 1974). Stands typically have open to moderate shrub cover with a herbaceous layer of scattered native forbs and grasses such as <i>Poa secunda</i>. However, disturbance-adapted species, such as  introduced <i>Bromus tectorum </i>, may invade stands and dominate the herb layer (Boul et al. 2021b). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Chrysothamnus viscidiflorus</i> is a widespread species and a common component of many alliances in California, including the <i>Artemisia arbuscula, Artemisia tridentata, Purshia tridentata - Artemisia tridentata</i>, and <i>Prunus emarginata - Holodiscus discolor</i> Alliances. Therefore it is important to note that true stands of this alliance do not have significant cover of <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> or <i>Purshia tridentata</i> (Boul et al. 2021b). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
